# Day 10 - File Permission Correction

## Task
Correct the ACL permissions on `/etc/hostname` on App Server 1:
- Owner and group must be `root`.
- Others must have read-only access.
- User `kareem` must have no permissions.
- User `rod` must have read-only access.

## Objective
Practice using Access Control Lists to apply per-user permissions beyond standard Linux `chmod` capabilities.

## Commands Used
```bash
ssh tony@stapp01

# Verify initial state
ls -la /etc/hostname

# Set owner and group to root
sudo chown root:root /etc/hostname

# Verify standard permissions are correct
sudo chmod 644 /etc/hostname

# Remove all permissions for kareem
sudo setfacl -m u:kareem:--- /etc/hostname

# Grant read-only to rod
sudo setfacl -m u:rod:r-- /etc/hostname

# Verify full ACL state
getfacl /etc/hostname
```

## What the Commands Do
- `chown root:root` sets the file owner and group to root.
- `chmod 644` sets standard permissions: owner reads/writes, group and others read only.
- `setfacl -m u:kareem:---` removes all permissions for a named user via ACL.
- `setfacl -m u:rod:r--` grants read-only access to a named user via ACL.
- `getfacl` displays the complete ACL including named user entries.

## Verification
```bash
getfacl /etc/hostname
```
```text
# owner: root
# group: root
user::rw-
user:kareem:---
user:rod:r--
group::r--
mask::r--
other::r--
```

## What I Learned
- How ACLs extend Linux permissions to support per-user access control.
- Why `chmod` cannot target named users and `setfacl` is required instead.
- How the `+` in `ls -la` output signals that ACL entries exist on a file.
- How `getfacl` provides the full permission picture including named user entries.

## Personal Notes
This task showed the practical difference between standard permissions and ACLs. The key takeaway is that `chmod` only works with owner, group, and others as categories, while `setfacl` allows fine-grained control per user.
